SALIVARY GLANDS (
Figs 69-72
). United, soft, not tumid, elongate, bilobed to Y-shaped; each duct leaving at the apex of the lobe and evenly thick throughout.

RADULA (
Figs 65-68
). (known from three species) With a unicuspid central tooth and 9 
-
15 laterals in each half-row, diminishing gradually in size laterally. Most or all laterals distinctively bicuspid or multicuspid, with outer cusps smaller or much smaller than inner cusps. Teeth are somewhat delicate (or flexible; 
Aiken 1981
) and are short and flake-like at the ventral end of the radular ribbon.
